What's new in Pega Process Fabric Hub 2.1
Pega Process Fabric Hub helps you connect and manage work from distributed applications across your enterprise by providing efficient, intuitive, and time-saving solutions. Key enhancements in this release of Pega Process Fabric Hub focus on exposing the list of assignments as a mashup gadget, enabling additional fields for assignments and cases, and providing APIs to support the publication of cases and associations to your remote application.

the new Pega Process Fabric Hub 2.1 comes with an out-of-the-box connector that you can conveniently implement to establish communication between your Pega Process Fabric Hub and Salesforce Platform instances. The connector enables you to manage work from multiple sources in the unified Pega Process Fabric Hub interface.

Interwoven Worklist available as a mashup gadget
You can now use the new Interwoven Worklist component, which consolidates assignments from your registered applications, as a mashup gadget in another Pega application, a non-Pega application, or on an external web page.

For more information, see Exposing Interwoven Worklist in other applications as a mashup gadget and Assignments management in Interwoven Worklist.

newDX APIs for customizing and exposing Interwoven Worklist beyond Pega Process Fabric Hub
You can now use DX APIs to fetch data from your Interwoven Worklist and expose the data externally to Pega Process Fabric Hub. DX APIs give you more customization options for the Interwoven Worklist UI than mashups and can also be used in Constellation environments.

For more information, see Exposing Interwoven Worklist and My cases data in other applications through DX API.

Additional fields for extending your data model
To better manage your assignments, you can now publish more data to new Pega Process Fabric Hub than the default data model provides, by adding custom fields for operators, assignments, associations, and cases.

For more information, see Extending Pega Process Fabric Hub data model with additional fields.

Data Synchronization APIs to support case and associations data publication
the new Pega Process Fabric Hub now provides APIs for publishing cases and associations. With the new APIs you can publish existing cases and associations in bulk, publish real-time cases, and provide URL information with each case entry.

For more information, see Endpoint for batch publishing of cases, Endpoint for real-time publishing of cases, Endpoint for batch publishing of associations, Endpoint for real-time publishing of associations, and Data Synchronization APIs for Pega Process Fabric Hub.

The My Cases landing page to enhance case management
The Pega Process Fabric Hub UI now contains the My Cases landing page, which displays all the cases that logged-in users follow. The landing page presents the most important information about the cases, such as case status, priority, and role, which reflects the current user's association with a given case. Users can choose to view cases with resolved or unresolved statuses. The Resolved cases view shows cases resolved in the last 30 days. The Name column includes links that open each case in a new window.

Archiving assignments and cases to improve system performance
In Pega Process Fabric Hub version 2.1 you can adjust the default archiving policy for assignments and cases. By archiving data, you save more storage space and also improve the search and reporting mechanisms.

For more information, see and Archival policy for assignments and cases.

Personas represent types of users that can interact with Pega Process Fabric Hub. Each persona has different available actions to perform and portals to access, based on its role in the organization. By understanding how different types of personas can operate, you can manage users more efficiently and ensure that every user has permissions to perform actions that directly relate to their responsibilities in the workflow.For example, a manager persona can view reports that contain data from registered applications, while a configurator persona can register remote applications with Pega Process Fabric Hub and manage application life cycle.
The following list contains the types of personas that are available in Pega Process Fabric Hub with short descriptions of corresponding roles and actions:
User
End users who have a user persona have access to a unified worklist on the Home landing page in Pega Process Fabric Hub. From this worklist, users who have this persona can obtain their prioritized work and use the Next Best Work algorithm to receive an assignment that Pega Process Fabric Hub estimates as the most important. In addition, the user persona can interact with work queues that the user associated with the persona can access. The user persona can also view a list of registered applications, but users who have this persona cannot take any action in an application life cycle.
Manager
End-users who have a manager persona typically have access to analytical data from registered applications that is available in Pega Process Fabric Hub Insights. End-users who have the manager persona also strive to increase throughput by properly planning and reassigning work in the remote application. Users who have this persona can access a unified worklist on the Home landing page and a list of registered applications, but they cannot take any action on an application life cycle.
Configurator
Users who have ta configurator persona are responsible for connections between remote applications and Pega Process Fabric Hub. A user with the configurator persona can register a remote application with Pega Process Fabric Hub, and then manage the application by performing actions that pertain to different business scenarios, such as updating work queues mappings or deactivating an application. The configurator persona can access a unified worklist and logs, as well as access and edit settings that affect the Next Best Work algorithm.
The following figure shows a page with application details that a configurator can access to view activity logs, manage application life cycle, and change application weighting:
Administrator
Users who have an administrator persona have the roles of all other personas that are available in Pega Process Fabric Hub. As a best practice, assign this persona to a user only in situations when the user must perform application-level actions from Dev Studio or Admin Studio, such as changing the production level of Pega Process Fabric Hub or managing queue processors that run in Pega Process Fabric Hub.
For more information, see Creating an administrative user for Pega Process Fabric Hub.

DataSyncAdministrator
Users who have a DataSyncAdministrator persona are responsible for data synchronization between Pega Process Fabric Hub and remote applications. This persona corresponds with the DataSyncOperator record. You do not assign this operator record to a specific user. Pega Process Fabric Hub includes this operator record by default, and for a proper data synchronization, you must avoid changing any configuration of this record.
Ensure that you enable the DataSyncOperator record that corresponds with the DataSyncAdministrator persona. If you host Pega Process Fabric Hub in Pega Cloud services environment, the operator is disabled by default. For more information, see Preparing Pega Process Fabric Hub for the Pega Cloud services environment.

Access groups associated with personas in Pega Process Fabric Hub
Access groups define which pages and actions that users of an application can perform. By analyzing and understanding access groups that are available for Pega Process Fabric Hub personas, you ensure that users can view pages and perform relevant actions.

Setting up Pega Process Fabric Hub
Pega Process Fabric Hub creates a consolidated list of assignments from different applications so that users save time and resources during work processing. Before you create connections between your applications and Pega Process Fabric Hub, learn how to correctly deploy Pega Process Fabric Hub.

You can deploy Pega Process Fabric Hub on Pega Platform versions 8.6, 8.7, and 8.8 in the following environments:
On the premises
In a Pega Cloud environment
On client-managed clouds
Depending on your instance of Pega Platform, the deployment process differs. If you install Pega Process Fabric Hub on the premises or on a client-managed cloud, you conduct an entire deployment process. If you host Pega Process Fabric Hub on Pega Cloud, Pega Cloud services perform an initial part of the deployment for you.

As part of the deployment process, you create an administrative user to manage Pega Process Fabric Hub, and update the Pega Process Fabric Hub keystore and related dynamic system settings.
To learn more about installing Pega Process Fabric Hub:
https://docs.pega.com/bundle/pega-process-fabric-hub-21/page/platform/pega-process-fabric/configuring-pega-process-fabric-hub.html
https://docs.pega.com/bundle/pega-process-fabric-hub-21/page/platform/pega-process-fabric/preparing-pega-process-fabric-hub-cloud.html
https://docs.pega.com/bundle/pega-process-fabric-hub-21/page/platform/pega-process-fabric/creating-administrative-user-pega-process-fabric-hub.html

Configuring Pega Process Fabric Hub
To provide users of your applications with uninterrupted, time-saving work environment, install Pega Process Fabric Hub in your Pega Platform environment. Pega Process Fabric Hub collects assignments from multiple applications so that users can save time processing various work items without switching context.

Note: Configuring Pega Process Fabric Hub applies to on-premises deployments of Pega Platform only. If you use Pega Process Fabric Hub in a Pega Cloud services environment, the Pega Cloud services team deploy Pega Process Fabric Hub for you. To request that Pega Cloud services install and configure Pega Process Fabric Hub in your environment, you must make a request by selecting New request in My Support Portal and include the networking details and operator details in the request. For the latest documentation on making requests, see My Support Portal: New Design, Streamlined Features. Ensure that you request hosting Pega Process Fabric Hub on an HTTPS port. For a Pega Cloud services environment, proceed with configuring an administrative user. For more information, see Creating an administrative user for Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Before you begin:
Prepare for Pega Process Fabric Hub installation:
Ensure that your Pega Platform environment is hosted on an HTTPS port and has valid certificates.
In your Pega Platform environment, create an application that you want to route assignments to Pega Process Fabric Hub. For more information, see Creating applications .
As Pega Process Fabric Hub opens assignments directly in the respective application, ensure that a default portal for users in an access group is the portal in which they process the assignments. For example, assign Your application:Managers access group to the Case Manager portal. For more information, see Granting portal access to an access group.
Create a request to obtain the PegaProcessFabricHub.jar product rule file. For more information, see Digital Delivery.
The Pega Process Fabric Hub installation adds the DataSyncOperator operator in your Pega Platform environment. Application registration and background processing rules reference the DataSyncOperator operator. You need this operator in your environment for various processes that are connected to Pega Process Fabric Hub.
In the header of Dev Studio, click Configure > Application > Distribution > Import.
On the Application: Import wizard tab, in the Import file section, select Local file, and then click Choose file.
In the file browser window, navigate to the PegaProcessFabricHub.jar product rule file, and then double-click the file.
On the Application: Import wizard tab, click Next.
In the File information section, select the Enable advanced mode to provide more granular control over the import process check box, and then click Next.
On the Operators tab, select the Enable new operators and overwrite existing operators on import check box, and then click Next.
Result:
Your system now includes the DataSyncOperator operator. Ensure that you enable the DataSyncOperator operator and then leave the operator unchanged. Editing fields in the operator rule form can cause issues during activating your applications and changing the operator's access group can cause the synchronization between your applications and Pega Process Fabric Hub to fail. If you leave the Enable new operators and overwrite existing operators on import, activation of remote applications fail.
On the No Changes tab, click Next.
On the Updates tab, click Next.
In the Aged Updates section, click Next.
After the import is complete, click Done.
Result:
Pega Process Fabric Hub is installed in your Pega Platform environment as a separate application. The following access groups are available in your system: PPF:Administrators, PPF:Configurators, PPF:Managers, and PPF:Users. Users with the PPF:Configurators access group can register applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub.
What to do next:
When Pega Process Fabric Hub is available in your Pega Platform environment, complete the following tasks:
Create operators for Pega Process Fabric Hub with IDs that are the same as operator IDs from remote applications that you want to communicate with Pega Process Fabric Hub. For more information, see Creating an operator ID.
Provide users with access to Pega Process Fabric Hub by assigning PPF:Configurators, PPF:Managers, and PPF:Users to operators. For more information, see Defining user contact information and application access .
If you host your Pega Process Fabric Hub application in a Pega Cloud environment, perform additional configurations that are specific for Pega Cloud. For more information, see Preparing Pega Process Fabric Hub for the Pega Cloud services environment.
Optionally, if your business scenario requires managing Pega Process Fabric Hub from Dev Studio and Admin Studio, configure an administrative user. For more information, see Creating an administrative user for Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Ensure that operators with the PPF:Configurators access group can check out rules. For more information, see Defining security information for an operator.
Create connections between Pega Process Fabric Hub and your applications so that Pega Process Fabric Hub can fetch data about assignments and operators. For more information, see Registering Pega applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub.

Preparing Pega Process Fabric Hub for the Pega Cloud services environment
Seamlessly manage your work from multiple applications by working with Pega Process Fabric Hub in your Pega Cloud services environment. As a result, you obtain a holistic view of the workflow in your organization from a single place, even if your business scenario includes cases and users from multiple applications.Additionally, for Pega Cloud services environments, you can start working faster as the Pega Cloud services deploy Pega Process Fabric Hub for you.
Before you begin:
To request that Pega Cloud services install and configure the Pega Process Fabric Hub in your environment, make a request by selecting New request in My Support Portal and include the networking details and operator details in the request. For the latest documentation on making requests, see?My Support Portal: New Design, Streamlined Features. Ensure to request hosting Pega Process Fabric Hub on an HTTPS port.
In order to work with Pega Process Fabric Hub in a Pega Cloud services environment, you need to create an administrative user, and then enable an operator that is responsible for synchronizing data between Pega Process Fabric Hub and your remote applications. Pega Process Fabric Hub includes the disabled DataSyncOperator operator by default.

Create an administrative user to manage Pega Process Fabric Hub.
For more information, see Creating an administrative user for Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Enable a DataSyncOperator operator to synchronize data between your remote applications and Pega Process Fabric Hub:
Log in to Dev Studio by using the administrative user credentials that you created in step 1.
In the navigation pane of Dev Studio, click Records.
Expand the Organization category, and then click Operator ID.
In the list of instances, click DataSyncOperator.
On the operator rule form, on the Security tab, clear the Disable Operator check box.
Click Save.
What to do next:
Create an administrative user to manage the Pega Process Fabric Hub resources. For more information, see Creating an administrative user for Pega Process Fabric Hub.

Creating an administrative user for Pega Process Fabric Hub
Ensure that a selected user can perform necessary actions on your Pega Process Fabric Hub application by creating an administrative user. An administrative user accumulates privileges for all other Pega Process Fabric Hub user types, and can also perform additional application-level actions in Dev Studio and Admin Studio.For example, an administrative user can log in to Admin Studio to analyze queue processors that run in Pega Process Fabric Hub, and change the production level of the Pega Process Fabric Hub application in Dev Studio. The administrative user also configures additional operators to log in to Pega Process Fabric Hub with an appropriate role, such as a manager, a user, or a configurator, along with relevant access mechanisms. The administrative user also sets up dynamic system settings related to the Pega Process Fabric Hub and configures the Pega Process Fabric Hub keystore.
Before you begin:
If you do not have your single sign-on (SSO) for Pega Platform configured yet, use administrator@pega.com as an ID and the supplied credentials.
You create an administrative user for Pega Process Fabric Hub by defining a new operator in Dev Studio and providing relevant settings during the creation process.
Note: Ensure that an administrative user performs actions on Pega Process Fabric Hub only in situations when changes are absolutely necessary.
In the header of Dev Studio, click Create > Organization > Operator ID.
On the Create Operator ID form, in the Short description field, enter the full name of the new operator.
In the Operator ID field, enter a unique identifier.
For example:
Enter PPFHubAdmin.
Click Create and open.
On the Profile tab, in the Application Access section, provide application access:
In the Access Group field, enter PPF:Administrators.
Optional: To set PPF:Administrators as the default access group, select a radio button next to the access group.
For example:
The following figure shows a configuration that sets PPF:Administrators as the default access group for the administrative user:
An operator rule form with the PPF:Administrators set as the default access group
Default access group setting
Update a password for the new operator:
On the Security tab, in the Access Settings section, click Update password.
In the Change Operator ID Password dialog box, in the New password and Confirm new password fields, enter a new password.
Note: Ensure that you enter identical values in both fields.
Click Submit.
On the Security tab, in the Access Settings section, select the Allow rule check out.
Result:
The administrative operator can check out rules to make changes in the Pega Process Fabric Hub application.
Click Save.
Result:
The administrative user can log in to Dev Studio to provide access to Pega Process Fabric Hub to more users and configure the Pega Process Fabric Hub dynamic system settings and keystore.
What to do next:
Define additional configurations for the administrative user:
Defining operator availability

Updating the Pega Process Fabric Hub keystore
Create a safe and secure connection between Pega Process Fabric Hub and your remote application by updating the Pega Process Fabric Hub keystore that Pega Process Fabric Hub uses to communicate with remote applications.

A keystore is a file that contains keys and certificates that you use for encryption, authentication, and serving content over HTTPS. You source a keystore from a data page, a URL, a keystore management service, or an external file. The Pega Process Fabric Hub includes a default keystore that expires, so you need to update the keystore by uploading a file. Pega Process Fabric Hub supports the following keystore types:
JKS
JWK
PKCS12
KEYTAB
KEY
Note: Updating the default PPFKP keystore Pega Process Fabric Hub is mandatory for the correct communication between Pega Process Fabric Hub and your remote application, because the default keystore might be expired.
Note: If your business scenario requires a keystore location other than an uploaded file, you need to delete the default PPFKP keystore and create a new keystore with the PPFKP name. For more information, see Creating a keystore for application data encryption .
In the navigation pane of Dev Studio, click Records.
Expand the Security category, and then click Keystore.
In the list of instances, select PPFKS.
Result:
The system displays the keystore rule form. By default, the system sources the PPFKS keystore location from the uploaded file. You cannot select a different keystore location.
On the Main tab of the keystore rule form, click Upload file.
In the Upload file dialog box, click Choose File.
In the dialog box, navigate to the file that you want to upload, and then click Open.
Click Upload file.
In the Keystore type field, select a keystore type that mathes your uploaded file.
In the Keystore password field, enter the password to secure the keystore.
Click Save.
Ensure that Pega Process Fabric Hub can correctly communicate with remote applications by updating the PPFToRemoteTokenGeneration token profile:
In the navigation pane of Dev Studio, click Records.
Expand the Security category, and then click Token Profile.
In the list of instances, select PPFToRemoteTokenGeneration.
On the Generation tab, in the Security section, in the Alias and Password fields, provide the values for the updated keystore.
For example:
The following figure shows the Security section of the token profile that includes the fields that store keystore alias and password:
Security section of the token profile rule form with updated keystore alias and password for the Pega Process Fabric Hub
Updating the token profile for Pega Process Fabric Hub
Note: Ensure that the keystore name is PPFKS.
Click Save.

Archival policy for assignments and cases
You can improve the performance of your system by adjusting the default archival policy for assignments and cases in your instance of Pega Process Fabric Hub. By archiving data, you save storage space and financial resources, and also improve search and reporting mechanisms.Additionally, archiving inactive assignments and cases increases performance for database queries and shortens database maintenance cycles.
During archiving, the system moves assignment and case data from Pega to Pega Cloud File storage. Pega Process Fabric Hub uses Pega Platform archiving functionality.

After deployment, Pega Process Fabric Hub includes a default Archival Policy data instance related to a Case and Task case type. Default archiving settings archive all the assignments and cases that are resolved within the last 365 days and permanently delete all the assignments and cases that were resolved earlier than 366 days.
Note: This capability is available only in Pega Cloud® services and on-premises Pega Platform version 8.7 with PostgreSQL, Oracle, or SQL database support.
Archiving assignments
Configure assignments archival to improve system performance and the search and reporting mechanisms.

In the navigation pane of Dev Studio, click App.
On the Classes tab, click Data-Retention-Policy.
In the list of class instances, click the class with the PPF-Work-Task class name that applies to the PegaProcessFabric ruleset, as shown in the following figure:
A list of class instances with a Pega Process Fabric hub archival policy class.
Opening archival policy class
Result:
The Archival Policy: Task class opens. By default, the Enable archival and Permanently delete archived data checkboxes are selected.
In the Archive cases that are resolved earlier than (in days) field, enter a number of days after which the system archives assignments that obtain a Resolved- status.
The default value is 365.
In the Permanently delete cases that are resolved earlier than (in days) field, enter a number of days after which the system deletes archived assignments with the Resolved- status from the Pega Cloud File storage.
The default value is 366. The value represents the number of days between the moment when the assignment obtains a Resolved- status and when the system can delete the assignment.
Note: Ensure that the value in the Permanently delete cases that are resolved earlier than (in days) field is greater than the value in the Archive cases that are resolved earlier than (in days) field because the system can only delete archived assignments.
Result:
After a specified number of days, the system deletes the archived assignment with the Resolved- status and the associated Elasticsearch index from the Pega Cloud File storage.
Optional: To configure archival policy in minutes instead of days, enable testing mode:
Select the Enable testing mode checkbox.
Select the Enable archival checkbox.
In the Archive cases that are resolved earlier than (in minutes) field, enter a number of minutes after which an assignment in the Resolved- status is available for archival.
Note: Testing mode is available only in non-production environments. In a production environment, you can configure archival policy in days only.
Click Save.

Configure a case archival policy to save storage space and improve system performance.

In the navigation pane of Dev Studio, click App.
On the Classes tab, click Data-Retention-Policy.
In the list of class instances, click the PPF-Work-Case class that applies to the PegaProcessFabric ruleset,
A list of class instances with a Pega Process Fabric Hub archival policy class.
Opening archival policy class
Result:
The Archival Policy: Case class opens in a new tab. By default, the Enable archival and Permanently delete archived data checkboxes are selected.
In the Archive cases that are resolved earlier than (in days) field, enter the number of days after which the system archives cases that obtain the Resolved- status.
The default value is 365.
In the Permanently delete cases that are resolved earlier than (in days) field, enter a number of days after which the system deletes archived cases with the Resolved- status from the Pega Cloud File storage.
The default value is 366. The value represents the number of days between the moment that a case obtains the Resolved- status and when the system can delete the case.
Note: Ensure that the value in the Permanently delete cases that are resolved earlier than (in days) field is greater than the value in the Archive cases that are resolved earlier than (in days) field because the system can delete only archived cases.
Result:
After the specified number of days, the system deletes archived cases with the Resolved- status and the associated Elasticsearch index from the Pega Cloud File storage.
Optional: To configure the archival policy in minutes instead of days, enable testing mode:
Select the Enable testing mode checkbox.
Select the Enable archival checkbox.
In the Archive cases that are resolved earlier than (in minutes) field, enter the number of minutes after which a case with the Resolved- status is available to be archived.
Note: Testing mode is available only in non-production environments. In a production environment, you can configure an archival policy in days only.
Click Save.

Pega Process Fabric Hub security dynamic system settings
Pega Process Fabric Hub includes a set of dynamic system setting rules that increase the security of connections between your applications and Pega Process Fabric Hub. As a result, you secure your application from any unauthorized or unauthenticated resources.

The following table lists the security dynamic system settings that your system receives when you install Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Note: The default values are recommended values to increase the security of your applications that you register with Pega Process Fabric Hub. Dynamic system settings are system-wide and might affect other applications that you deploy on the same system as Pega Process Fabric Hub. Before you move your applications to the production environment, conduct thorough testing to ensure that all your applications operate correctly.
Column

Filter
Filter
prconfig/HTTP/SetSecureCookie/default	true	Prevents the exposure of the session ID cookie and also prevents session hijacking as the browser sends cookies only across SSL protocols.	Security
prconfig/initialization/DisableAutoComplete/default	true	Prevents client-side storage of user name and password combinations. Use this setting when you clear any existing stored sensitive information in the browser.	Browser data

Note: For the security/csrf/allowReferrersWithExactMatchOnly CSRF-related dynamic system setting, ensure that the value is false. For the remaining settings, ensure that the values match your needs.

Registering and managing remote applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub
Remote applications publish data to Pega Process Fabric Hub so that users can acquire a holistic view of the workflow in their organization, and consequently resolve work faster. By learning about remote applications, you can prepare to implement resource-saving solutions in your enterprise.

Remote applications are applications in your organization that users use to process work, and that you want to connect to Pega Process Fabric Hub. Consider a scenario in which users log in to the following applications to process assignments:
New hires recruitment
Timesheets approval
Expenses request and approval
After you connect those remote applications to Pega Process Fabric Hub, users can view and interact with a consolidated list of assignments from all of these applications. As a result, users can plan and perform their work more efficiently.
Remote applications are responsible for data publication as Pega Process Fabric Hub only accepts data. For this reason, understanding how to connect a remote application to Pega Process Fabric Hub is crucial for creating correct communication between the applications. You can connect applications that you host on instances of Pega Platform in the following environments:
On the premises
In a Pega Cloud environment
On client-managed clouds
To initialize data publication to Pega Process Fabric Hub, you first register and then activate a remote application in Pega Process Fabric Hub. When the remote application is active, you can manage an application life cycle by performing actions that are relevant to your business circumstances. For example, you can pause data publication to Pega Process Fabric Hub when you update your remote application, and then reactivate the connection when the update is complete. You can conveniently manage applications directly from Pega Process Fabric Hub.

You can connect remote applications both from the same and from different instances of Pega Platform that you use to host your Pega Process Fabric Hub application.

To meet your unique business needs, you can also connect non-Pega applications to Pega Process Fabric Hub. If you host your remote application outside Pega Platform, use REST APIs to create the connection between Pega Process Fabric Hub and your application, and then to manage the application life cycle. For more information, see Building custom connectors for Pega Process Fabric Hub.
To learn more about remote applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub, see the following articles:
https://docs.pega.com/bundle/pega-process-fabric-hub-21/page/platform/pega-process-fabric/registering-pega-applications-pega-process-fabric.html

Registering Pega applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub
For seamless management of work that include assignments from multiple applications, register your applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub. By using a unified worklist in Pega Process Fabric Hub, you save time and provide a consistent user experience.
Before you begin:
Prepare to register your applications:
Ensure that the application that you want to register is present on a Pega Platform system that supports HTTPS and has valid certificates.
Ensure that the operator IDs in the system that hosts your applications and in the system that hosts Pega Process Fabric Hub are identical. The operator ID is case-sensitive. Other operator details can differ between the systems.
Ensure that you have an Application:Administrators, Application:Authors, or your custom access group with administrative privileges in the system that hosts your applications.
Note: If you use a custom access group other than Application:Administrators or Application:Authors, add the access group to the AllowedRegistrationAccessGroups dynamic system setting. For more information, see Modification of the standard mappings published to Pega Process Fabric Hub and Editing a dynamic system setting . Ensure that the access group is present in your operator record. For more information, see Defining user contact information and application access .
In Pega Process Fabric Hub, you can use Interwoven Worklist that consolidates assignments from your numerous registered applications. By using Interwoven Worklist, users save time and complete daily assignments without switching context between many applications.

Register your applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub by completing the following tasks:
https://docs.pega.com/bundle/pega-process-fabric-hub-21/page/platform/pega-process-fabric/importing-pega-process-fabric-hub-connector-component.html

Installing the Pega Process Fabric Hub connector component
o connect your applications to Pega Process Fabric Hub, download and install the Pega Process Fabric Hub connector component in your remote application that you want to register with Pega Process Fabric Hub.The component is responsible for tracking the creation of new assignments and publishing assignment details to Pega Process Fabric Hub. The component also provides all the necessary transformation capabilities before publishing assignments.
Before you begin:
Download the Pega Process Fabric component from Pega Marketplace. Ensure that the component that you download matches the version of your instance of Pega Platform. For more information, see Pega Process Fabric Hub connector for Pega Platform.
Note: You only install the Pega Process Fabric component once on your Pega Platform system. The installation impacts all the applications in your Pega Platform system.
In the header of Dev Studio, click the name of the application, and then click Definition.

Modification of the standard mappings published to Pega Process Fabric Hub
Extensions pass fields from your application to Pega Process Fabric Hub so that Pega Process Fabric Hub reflects data from your application. Overriding default extensions maps the values between your application and Pega Process Fabric Hub in a way that is accurate for your unique business scenario.Additional fields that Pega Process Fabric Hub includes are Customer, Product, and Account. With the additional fields, you can present more detailed assignment data in Pega Process Fabric Hub. If your application stores related data in fields with different names, by overriding default extensions, you ensure that information between your application and Pega Process Fabric Hub passes correctly.
Standard assignment data

Pega Process Fabric Hub includes the following standard fields to store assignment data:
RegistrationID
AssingTo
AssignToType
CaseTypeClass
Status
TaskID
Label
Priority
TaskCreateDateTime
TaskCreateOperator
The Customer, Product, and Account fields are additional and you can use these fields to pass more detailed data to Pega Process Fabric Hub by using extensions.

You add the Pega Process Fabric extensions to your application when you install the Pega Process Fabric Hub connector component. The extensions use both bulk sync and real-time APIs to pass data from your applications to Pega Process Fabric Hub. If you want to pass values from fields in your application, first you need to identify the class that stores the field value in your Pega Platform system.

The Assign- classes

To pass values that the system stores in the Assign-Worklist or Assign-WorkBasket classes, you override the following items:
The Assign-Worklist.pyPF_PublishBulk and Assign-WorkBasket.pyPF_PublishBulk report definitions by adding your columns to these reports.
The bulk sync that runs during the registration activation process uses these reports to fetch assignment data from the database. However, real-time sync uses assignment BLOB for sourcing assignment data. As a result, overriding the Assign-Worklist.pyPF_PublishBulk and Assign-WorkBasket.pyPF_PublishBulk report definitions impacts only bulk sync.

The Assign-.pyPF_SetRequest data transform by adding your field, for example RequestPage.label = Primary.pxTaskLabel.
Both bulk sync and real-time sync use this data transform to prepare the task request.

The Work- classes

To pass values that the system stores in your Work- class, you override the following items:
The Work-.pyPF_GetCases report definition by adding your column to this report.
Both bulk sync and real-time sync use this report definition to fetch case information in the task request preparation.

The Work-.pyPF_SetRequest data transform by adding your field, for example the RequestPage.caseLabel = Primary.pyLabel format.
Both bulk sync and real-time sync use this data transform to prepare the task request.

Other classes

If the value belongs to a class that is different than the Assign- or Work- class, you override the System-Queue-PPF-Connect-Assign data transform by adding your field, for example RequestPage.accountID = Primary.pyAccountId. Both bulk sync and real-time sync use this data transform to prepare the task request.

Order of preference

Avoid including a field in multiple extensions. However, if your business process requires the same field in multiple extensions, the system considers classes that store fields in the following order:
The System-Queue-PPF-Connect-Assign.pyPF_SetRequest data transform
Your Work- class
The Work- class
The Assign- class
For example, if you include the same field in the Work- and Assign- classes, the system references the field from the Work- class.

Pega Process Fabric Hub Connector for Salesforce Platform
Pega Process Fabric Hub provides an out-of-the-box connector that you can implement to communicate with your instance of Salesforce Platform and manage work from multiple sources in a unified interface.As a result, case workers can process work more efficiently without the need to switch contexts. Pega Process Fabric Hub also provides an aggregated overview of the workflow in your enterprise so that work management is more efficient and comprehensible, even if workers use numerous applications.
Note: This chapter focuses on Pega Platform functionality with an assumption that you are familiar with Salesforce Platform. For more information about Salesforce Platform and related functionalities, refer to Salesforce documentation.
Important: The Pega Process Fabric Hub Connector component for Salesforce is a product offered fully by Pegasystems. Salesforce does not offer, sponsor, or endorse Pega Process Fabric Hub Connector for Salesforce, and Pegasystems does not offer, sponsor, or endorse any Salesforce products.
Pega Process Fabric Hub Connector for Salesforce Platform comes with the following functionalities:
Tracks the creation of entities in Salesforce Platform and publishes the information of entities to Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Provides all the necessary transformation capabilities before publishing entities so that Pega Process Fabric Hub can accept data that is in the correct format.
Enables applications to publish information about entities such as Opportunity, Work Order, work queues, and operators to work queue mappings from your Salesforce Platform.
If you want to host your connector in the same Pega Process Fabric Hub instance, use Salesforce Application, which is the Pega out-of-the-box wrapper application with the Pega Process Fabric Hub Connector component built-in.
Alternatively, you can host your connector in an independent remote system. In such a case, you create a Pega wrapper application and install the Pega Process Fabric Hub Connector component for Salesforce Platform in your wrapper application. For more information, see Installing the connector component for Salesforce Platform.
When communication is established, Salesforce Platform publishes information about entities, such as Opportunity and Work Order, work queues, and operators, to the Pega wrapper. Then, the wrapper application publishes the data that it receives to Pega Process Fabric Hub. After you connect your Salesforce Platform to Pega Process Fabric Hub through the wrapper application, a bulk sync occurs, and all entity-related data is available in Pega Process Fabric Hub. Then, Pega Process Fabric Hub displays updates of the entity data in real time.
https://docs.pega.com/bundle/pega-process-fabric-hub-21/page/platform/pega-process-fabric/configuring-salesforce-platform-connect-pega-process-fabric-hub.html#sfdc-configuring-salesforce-application-to-connect-with-the-pega-process-fabric-hub-tsk

Configuring Salesforce Platform to connect with Pega Process Fabric Hub
Seamlessly manage your work from multiple sources by configuring your Salesforce Platform to communicate with Pega Process Fabric Hub in real time, through the wrapper application. As a result, you gain a unified interface that aggregates data from remote applications and helps workers resolve work faster without switching context.

To prepare a connection between your instance of Salesforce Platform and Pega Process Fabric Hub, you need to obtain Salesforce credentials and a security token, and then call a series of Salesforce Tooling APIs to prepare a communication channel and fields to map data from your Salesforce Platform to Pega Process Fabric Hub.

Important: The Pega Process Fabric Hub Connector component for Salesforce is a product offered fully by Pegasystems. Salesforce does not offer, sponsor, or endorse Pega Process Fabric Hub Connector for Salesforce, and Pegasystems does not offer, sponsor, or endorse any Salesforce products.
Obtaining Salesforce credentials
Connect your Salesforce Platform to Pega Process Fabric Hub through a wrapper application by obtaining a Salesforce security token.The security token and your Salesforce user name are required to register the wrapper application with Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Before you begin:
Ensure that you use a version of Salesforce Platform other than the trial version.
In Salesforce Platform, create a connected app by enabling OAuth authorization settings for Salesforce API integration.
For more information, refer to Salesforce documentation on creating a connected app.
Configure OAuth access policies for OAuth-enabled connected app.
The access policies include defining which users can access a connected app, what IP restrictions apply to the connected app, and how long a refresh token is valid. For more information, refer to Salesforce documentation on managing OAuth access policies for a connected app.
In the connected app, copy the consumer key and consumer secret, and then save the values on your local machine.
For more information about navigating to consumer credentials, refer to Salesforce documentation.
Obtain a security token by resetting the security token in your connected app.
For more information about the security token, refer to Salesforce documentation.
Result:
You receive an email with the new security token. Ensure that you keep the email, because the security token is required for registering a wrapper application with Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Configuring a Salesforce custom event channel and change event enrichment
For real-time updates between your Salesforce Platform and Pega Process Fabric Hub, subscribe to a custom channel by creating an event channel and adding event enrich fields. As a result, you ensure that Pega Process Fabric Hub displays the most accurate and latest data from your remote system.

You can create custom event channels for any Salesforce entities required by your business scenario. Standard Salesforce entities include Opportunity and Work Order. Salesforce publishes entity information to the custom event channel. Pega Process Fabric Hub Connector in a wrapper application monitors the channel and then publishes information to Pega Process Fabric Hub. Fields that you include in the custom event channel are mapped to fields in the assignment data in Pega Process Fabric Hub.
For detailed steps please check https://docs.pega.com/bundle/pega-process-fabric-hub-21/page/platform/pega-process-fabric/configuring-salesforce-platform-connect-pega-process-fabric-hub.html

Configuring a Pega Platform wrapper application
To establish communication between your Salesforce Platform and Pega Process Fabric Hub, configure a Pega Platform application as a wrapper. As a result, you ensure correct mapping of data and real-time updates between your remote Salesforce system and Pega Process Fabric Hub.

A wrapper application functions as a buffer between your Salesforce Platform and Pega Process Fabric Hub.
When communication is established, Salesforce Platform publishes information about entities, such as Opportunity and Work Order, work queues, and operators, to the Pega wrapper. Then, the wrapper application publishes the data that it receives to Pega Process Fabric Hub. After you connect your Salesforce Platform to Pega Process Fabric Hub through the wrapper application, a bulk sync occurs, and all entity-related data is available in Pega Process Fabric Hub. Then, Pega Process Fabric Hub displays updates of the entity data in real time.

If you want to host your connector in the same Pega Process Fabric Hub instance, you can configure Salesforce Application, which is an out-of-the-box wrapper application in Pega Platform, to meet your business goals, such as modifying or publishing more entities.
If you want to host your connector in an independent remote system, create a Pega Platform wrapper application, and then install the Pega Process Fabric Hub Connector component for Salesforce Platform and configure the Pega Platform wrapper application.
Note: After you configure a wrapper, you have to install a set of external JAR files to ensure that the communication between your wrapper application and your instance of Salesforce Platform works correctly. For more information, see External jars and an application used in the Pega Process Fabric Hub connector for Salesforce Platform.
To learn more about configuring a Pega Platform wrapper application, see the following articles:

The component is responsible for tracking the creation of new entities and publishing the details of the entities to Pega Process Fabric Hub. The component also provides all the necessary transformation capabilities before publication.

Important: The Pega Process Fabric Hub Connector component for Salesforce is a product offered fully by Pegasystems. Salesforce does not offer, sponsor, or endorse Pega Process Fabric Hub Connector for Salesforce, and Pegasystems does not offer, sponsor, or endorse any Salesforce products.

Registering and activating a wrapper application in Pega Process Fabric Hub
Process work from your remote Salesforce Platform in a unified interface by activating your wrapper application in Pega Process Fabric Hub. After you register and activate your wrapper application, you can take advantage of features such as Interwoven Worklist or Pega Process Fabric Hub Insights, to analyze and process Salesforce entities.

Managing applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub
Respond in a flexible way to dynamically changing business objectives by governing the life cycle of the applications that you connect to Pega Process Fabric Hub. As a result, you ensure that Pega Process Fabric Hub reflects the actual work in your organization. You also save time because you can manage the connections between all your applications and Pega Process Fabric Hub on one screen.For example, you can stop synchronization with an application that currently is not in use in your organization, so that Pega Process Fabric Hub stops syncing data with the application. Later, you can start the synchronization again when the business circumstances change.
Manage your remote applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub by performing the following actions:
Updating work queue data
Resynchronize mapping between work queues and operators in Pega Process Fabric Hub to reflect latest changes in your organization, and to ensure that Pega Process Fabric Hub correctly routes work.For example, you can update work queue data after you create new work queues in your remote application and associate them with users, or when associations between users and work queues change.
In the navigation pane of Pega Process Fabric Hub, click Registered applications.
In the Registered applications section, click the application for which you want to update mapping.
Click Actions > Update work queue data.
In the Update work queue data dialog box, click Update.

Manually deleting the connection between Pega Process Fabric Hub and a remote application
To manage resources and facilitate routing assignments, delete a remote application from Pega Process Fabric Hub even when you cannot access this action from the application life cycle.For example, when your remote application no longer pertains to your business scenario, to stop publishing data from the remote application to Pega Process Fabric Hub, delete the application from Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Before you begin:
Obtain a PPF:Administrators access group to delete applications from Pega Process Fabric Hub. For more information, see Defining user contact information and application access and Access groups associated with personas in Pega Process Fabric Hub.
As a best practice, to delete an application, manage the application life cycle. However, for specific scenarios the ability to delete an application through the application life cycle is unavailable. One example is when queue processors that correspond to Pega Process Fabric Hub have invalid configuration. As a result, you might not be able to change the application status from Sync-InProgress. In such situations, manually delete the connection, first on the Pega Process Fabric Hub side, and then in the remote application. The connection stops working when you delete the rules that Pega Process Fabric Hub saved in the remote application.
For more info check https://docs.pega.com/bundle/pega-process-fabric-hub-21/page/platform/pega-process-fabric/manually-deleting-connection-pega-process-fabric-hub-remote-application.html

Viewing error logs in Pega Process Fabric Hub
To ensure that users can process their work, fix any issues that might hinder Pega Process Fabric Hub from fetching assignments from your applications. You can quickly identify any issues by viewing and analyzing the log messages.For example, you can learn that an assignment does not have correct routing settings and that you need to specify the worklist that receives the task.
Before you begin:
You need to have a PPF:Administrators or PPF:Configurators access group to view error logs. For more information, see Defining user contact information and application access .
The Error logs page lists the errors that occur when an application publishes data to Pega Process Fabric Hub in an incorrect way. You can quickly determine in which assignment, case type, or application an error occurred. First, you can get a quick overview of the issue by analyzing a short description of the issue in the Error column, and you can then view the JSON of the error log to identify the request that Pega Process Fabric Hub received. When you know what causes the issue, you can log in to the relevant application to fix the problem by making the required changes, so that the users who process assignments in Pega Process Fabric Hub can bring their cases to a successful resolution. Assignments that include incorrect data are shown on the Error logs page only, because Pega Process Fabric Hub omits them from Interwoven Worklist.
For detailed steps check https://docs.pega.com/bundle/pega-process-fabric-hub-21/page/platform/pega-process-fabric/viewing-errors-logs-pega-process-fabric.html

Next Best Work in Pega Process Fabric Hub
For improved workload management, ensure that users process the most important assignments first by engaging the Next Best Work logic to select assignments. When users open an assignment by using the Next Best Work option, Pega Process Fabric Hub prompts them to take the work that the Next Best Work algorithm evaluates as the most important.

When a user chooses the Next Best Work option to open the next assignment, the algorithm evaluates tasks both from the user's worklist and the work queues to which the user has access. A worklist displays open assignments that applications route directly to a specific user. Every user has a unique worklist of tasks to complete. A work queue is a list of open assignments that are available to a group of users. When an application routes an assignment to a work queue, any user that has access to the work queue can pick up the assignment. For example, in a banking application, every customer service representative (CSR) has their own worklist with the assignments that they need to complete. Additionally, CSRs who are responsible for processing loans can access a work queue that contains assignments that are only related to loan requests.

The Next Best Work algorithm uses the following factors to select the most appropriate assignment to open:

Urgency
Each assignment has an initial urgency of 10. To meet your unique business needs, you can edit the initial urgency for all the assignments in a case type by editing the case type settings. The urgency changes through a case life cycle when a goal and a deadline for an assignment passes. The total maximum urgency is 100. In Interwoven Worklist, the urgency matches the priority.
Weighting
Each application registered in Pega Process Fabric Hub has a weighting that indicates the importance of the assignments that the application routes. The default weighting is 1. You can associate an application with a weighting ranging from 1 to 10. The value that you define applies to all the assignments that the application routes.
To evaluate which assignment has the highest importance, the Next Best Work algorithm multiples the urgency by the weighting of the available assignments, and then opens the assignment with the highest score.

To ensure that users avoid duplicating work, after a user opens the assignment, Pega Process Fabric Hub makes the assignment unavailable to other users and omits the assignment from the Next Best Work algorithm. The Next Best Work algorithm considers both assignments from the worklist of the current user and the work queues that the user can access.
https://docs.pega.com/bundle/pega-process-fabric-hub-21/page/platform/pega-process-fabric/setting-weightage-applications.html

Working with assignments in Pega Process Fabric Hub
Pega Process Fabric Hub offers tools to manage assignments to make workflow in your enterprise more efficient. Apart from accessing work routed from multiple applications, users can group and filter assignments for a clearer view of their workload.

Pega Process Fabric Hub provides the following features to help users manage assignments more efficiently:
Interwoven Worklist
A consolidated list that gathers assignments from a worklist and work queues that a specific user can access. Users can filter and group assignments to meet their business needs. For example, users can group assignments by application or order the assignments based on priority.
Next Best Work
An algorithm that prompts users to pick up assignments with the highest importance. The algorithm includes the assignment urgency and the routing application in the calculations. Users with the configurator persona can adjust the algorithm by changing application weighting.

Assignments management in Interwoven Worklist
To improve daily work experience of case workers, provide a consolidated list of assignments that different application route. Use Interwoven Worklist that offers both solutions for efficient work management and a holistic view on the workload. Interwoven Worklist includes all tasks that are routed to a specific worklist or work queue.

A worklist displays open assignments that applications route directly to a specific user. Every user has a unique worklist of tasks to complete. A work queue is a list of open assignments that are available to a group of users, for example to all members of one team.

Interwoven Worklist is one of the functionalities that are available in Pega Process Fabric Hub. Interwoven Worklist collects all assignments that are assigned to a user from multiple registered applications, even across various Pega Platform systems and versions, starting with Pega Platform 8.1. As a result, users save time because they can access all their assignments in a single window, without switching between applications to check their worklists. Interwoven Worklist also provides better workload management because users can view a full list of assignments with due dates and priorities. Consequently, assignees can make informed decisions about which assignment to resolve next by taking into consideration tasks from across all their applications at once.

Interwoven Worklist synchronizes with applications in real time, which means that users receive information immediately after an application routes an assignment, as show on the following figure:

Interwoven Worklist with a real-time notification about a new assignment
Real-time notifications
To avoid duplicating work, Interwoven Worklist marks completed assignments and makes them unavailable for users to pick up, both in worklists and work queues. In a work queue, Interwoven Worklist prevents users form picking up assignments on which another user already works.

After clicking an assignment link, Pega Process Fabric Hub redirects users to an application that includes the assignment. Users can work on the assignment directly in the application context.
Note: If you want to provide a user with an ability to pick up assignments from work queues, ensure that you assign the user to a specific work queue. For more information, see Defining work routing settings for an operator .
For more sufficient workload management and enhanced prioritization, users can use Next Best Work algorithm to pick up tasks. The algorithm evaluates priority of assignments by multiplying assignment urgency and weighting that you can configure for every application. As a result, Next Best Work provides an assignment with the highest score.

Grouping assignments in Pega Process Fabric Hub
To access the information that you need faster and to plan your work more efficiently, group the assignments in Pega Process Fabric Hub in a method that best complies with your business needs.For example, you can group your assignments by priority, and then sort all the assignments with the same priority by an application. Depending on your purpose, you can group the assignments that are available in your Interwoven Worklist, and in Pega Process Fabric Hub Insights. In Interwoven Worklist, you can get a holistic view of all the assignments that are available for you to resolve, while Pega Process Fabric Hub Insights offers a complete overview of work progress across your organization.
