Pega Process Fabric Hub is an application that facilitates consolidation of work from multiple distributed applications. With Pega Process Fabric Hub, you save time and increase efficiency because users can perform work without switching context several times during a workday. You can also get a holistic overview of the workflow from all the applications that you connect to Pega Process Fabric Hub.

General
What organizations can benefit from implementing Pega Process Fabric Hub?
Pega Process Fabric Hub is especially suitable for organizations that use multiple decentralized applications that are hosted on different systems.

What is Pega Process Fabric Hub?
Pega Process Fabric Hub is a tool to connect and orchestrate work from multiple distributed applications. Pega Process Fabric Hub includes the following functionalities:
Interwoven Worklist
A tool that collects assignments from remote registered applications that synchronize with Pega Process Fabric Hub. Interwoven Worklist creates a cumulative worklist that is unique to every user, as well as work queues that multiple users can share. The applications can synchronize assignment data with Pega Process Fabric Hub in real time, to avoid duplicating work and ensure that the latest versions of the worklists and work queues are available. Applications can also re-synchronize any changes related to work queues and operator mappings, to provide updated and accurate workflow in your organization.
Pega Process Fabric Application Registry
A portal that lists all your applications registered with Pega Process Fabric Hub. For active applications, you can view activity logs to analyze how the connection between your applications and Pega Process Fabric Hub works. You can also manage the life cycle of your applications, for example, to stop synchronizing with applications that are temporarily out of use.
Pega Process Fabric Hub Insights
A reporting tool that you use to generate data about the workflow in your registered applications. For example, you can view how many high priority open assignments are currently assigned to worklists and work queues in Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Next Best Work
The Next best Work algorithm helps users prioritize work by prompting the assignments with the highest importance from a worklist and work queues that the user can access. The Next Best Work algorithm multiplies the urgency of an assignment by the weighting of the application that routes the assignment, and then returns work with the highest score. As a result, users can quickly and automatically pick up work that is currently the most urgent.
For more information, see Pega Process Fabric Hub and Next Best Work in Pega Process Fabric Hub.

How do I obtain Pega Process Fabric Hub and its connector for remote applications?
You download Pega Process Fabric Hub from Digital Delivery and you download the Pega Process Fabric Hub connector for remote applications from the Process Fabric Connector page on Pega Marketplace.

What Pega Platform applications can I register with Pega Process Fabric Hub?
You can register applications that you host in Pega Platform version 8.1 and later. You can register applications that you host on the following deployments:
On-premises Pega Platform deployments
Deployments in Pega Cloud services
Pega Platform deployments on client-managed clouds
Pega Process Fabric Hub does not support applications that you host in Pega Platform version 7.4 and earlier.

For more information, see Pega Process Fabric Hub and Registering Pega applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub.

On what structure does Pega Process Fabric Hub rely?
Pega Process Fabric Hub relies on case types and case assignments and fetches data about assignments that users complete as part of case processing. For Pega Platform applications, Pega Process Fabric Hub does not support any other types of tasks, such as tasks that you create in Pulse, or in spaces.

For more information, see Pega Process Fabric Hub.

What personas does Pega Process Fabric Hub support?
Pega Process Fabric Hub supports the following types of personas:
Users
Standard type of persona for any user with a PPF:Users access group. A user can open assignments from their worklist and work queues and use the Next Best Work algorithm to prompt work.
Managers
Managerial type of persona for users with a PPF:Managers access group. A manager can open assignments from their worklist and work queues, use the Next Best Work algorithm, and view reports in Pega Process Fabric Hub Insights.
Configurators
Administrative type of persona for users with a PPF:Configurators access group. Administrators can register applications with Pega Process Fabric Hub, manage application life cycles in Pega Process Fabric Hub, and change weighting for applications to modify data for the Next Best Work algorithm. Users with the PPF:Configurators access group can open assignments and use the Next Best Work algorithm, similarly to other types of users.
For more information, see Understanding personas in Pega Process Fabric Hub.

How does licensing for Pega Process Fabric Hub work?
The license for Pega Platform includes Pega Process Fabric Hub. Connecting non-Pega applications might require the coverage of additional costs. For more information, contact your Account Manager.

Managing assignments and calculating urgency
If I have a common work queue configured across multiple applications that are deployed on the same server, how does Pega Process Fabric Hub display this work queue?
Pega Process Fabric Hub synchronizes assignments, work queues, and operator mappings per registered application, and the remote application publishes this information during activation. When multiple applications use the same work queue, the work queue data synchronizes per application. In such scenario, a user of Pega Process Fabric Hub can view multiple entries for one work queue, and each entry corresponds to a different application. Also, Pega Process Fabric Hub displays an application context for each entry. As a result, when a user selects a work queue entry for a specific application, Interwoven Worklist displays assignments that come from the selected application only.

For more information, see Assignments management in Interwoven Worklist.

How does Pega Process Fabric Hub prompt the most important work for a selected user?
Pega Process Fabric Hub uses the Next Best Work algorithm to select an assignment that is currently the most important. The Next Best Work algorithm considers the urgency of an assignment and the weighting of the application that routes the assignment, and then prompts a user with the assignment with the highest score.

For more information, see Next Best Work in Pega Process Fabric Hub.

Can I customize the Next Best Work algorithm?
Currently, the Next Best Work algorithm relies on providing a weighting for the application and supports no customizations.

For more information, see Next Best Work in Pega Process Fabric Hub.

How does Pega Process Fabric Hub calculate urgency for assignments from applications that have non-integer urgency?
Because Pega Process Fabric Hub only accepts data from remote applications, to calculate non-integer urgency, ensure that you map the urgency format from your remote application to the format that Pega Process Fabric Hub uses for calculations. Pega Process Fabric Hub calculates urgency for assignments with an integer-based urgency which value is between 0 and 100.

For more information, see Next Best Work in Pega Process Fabric Hub.

Does the Next Best Work algorithm consider skills that I assign to users during routing assignments?
No, the Next Best Work algorithm considers only application weighting and the urgency of an assignment.

For more information, see Next Best Work in Pega Process Fabric Hub.

Can users interact with all assignments that remote applications route to Pega Process Fabric Hub?
Users with a standard user persona in Pega Process Fabric Hub can process assignments that a remote application routes to their worklist or a work queue that the user can access. Routing and access configurations rely on a side of a remote application. Users with a manager persona in Pega Process Fabric Hub can access an overview of assignment data in Pega Process Fabric Hub without an option to process any assignments.

For more information, see Understanding personas in Pega Process Fabric Hub.

How does Pega Process Fabric Hub ensure that users do not duplicate work?
If a user picks up an assignment from a work queue that multiple users share, or by using Next Best Work, Pega Process Fabric Hub makes the assignment unavailable to other users. Because applications sync data with Pega Process Fabric Hub in real time, the assignment that is under processing is also unavailable from the remote application interface.

For more information, see Assignments management in Interwoven Worklist.

How does Pega Process Fabric Hub handle assignments that a remote application routes to a work group or a team?
When a remote application routes an assignment to a work group or team, the assignment moves to a work queue or worklist according to the configuration in the remote application. Then, Pega Process Fabric Hub displays the assignment to the target user if the assignment moves to a worklist, or to all users who can access a work queue if the assignment moves to a work queue.

For more information, see Assignments management in Interwoven Worklist.

Registering and managing applications
Who can register remote Pega Platform applications with Pega Process Fabric Hub?
In your remote Pega Platform application, ensure that you assign one of the following access groups to an operator who wants to register applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub:
ApplicationName:Authors
ApplicationName:Administrators
A custom access group with administrative privileges
Note: If you use a custom access group other than Application:Administrators or Application:Authors, add the access group to the AllowedRegistrationAccessGroups dynamic system setting. For more information, see Modification of the standard mappings published to Pega Process Fabric Hub and Editing a dynamic system setting . Ensure that the access group is present in your operator record. For more information, see Defining user contact information and application access .
A user who wants to register applications with Pega Process Fabric Hub also needs to have the PPF:Configurators access group in the Pega Process Fabric Hub application.

You define access groups for operators in Dev Studio. For more information, see Learning about access groups.

When I register a new application, I select the application from the list in the Register application dialog box. How does Pega Process Fabric Hub populate this list?
In the Register application dialog box, Pega Process Fabric Hub displays all remote applications from a selected system. The applications include the Pega Process Fabric Hub Connector component and are unregistered with Pega Process Fabric Hub yet.

Can I delete a registered application from Pega Process Fabric Hub?
Yes, you can delete registered Pega and non-Pega applications from Pega Process Fabric Hub. Only users with a configurator persona can delete applications. Deleting applications from Pega Process Fabric Hub removes the connection between Pega Process Fabric Hub and your remote application, as well as resources that are synchronized with Pega Process Fabric Hub, such as operators and work queue mappings. The remote application remains intact in the hosting system.

For more information, see Deleting applications from Pega Process Fabric Hub.

Is there a limit to the number of applications that I can register in Pega Process Fabric Hub?
You can register remote applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub without a limit.

How often do remote applications synchronize with Pega Process Fabric Hub?
After you register a remote application in Pega Process Fabric Hub, a bulk sync of all open assignments in the remote application occurs. After registration, a remote application synchronizes with Pega Process Fabric Hub in real time, every time on creation of a new assignment, and on update or completion of an existing assignment.

For more information, see Assignments management in Interwoven Worklist.

Can I schedule a bulk sync after I register a new application to occur after working hours?
Currently, Pega Process Fabric Hub does not support customization of bulk sync when you register a new application. The bulk sync occurs automatically after you activate a new application. You can manually activate the new application after peak hours when the data throughput is lower. Other changes in assignment data in the remote application synchronize automatically in real time with Pega Process Fabric Hub.

For more information, see Activating applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub.

If I move my remote application to the offline mode, how can I stop users in Pega Process Fabric Hub from seeing assignments from this application?
To prevent users from interacting with assignments from a remote application, disable the application in Pega Process Fabric Hub.

For more information, see Disabling and enabling applications.

After I create a new operator in my remote application, does this operator automatically gain access to Pega Process Fabric Hub?
No, new operator data requires resynchronizing the work queue data with Pega Process Fabric Hub.

For more information, see Updating work queue data.

Can I register non-Pega applications directly from Pega Process Fabric Hub interface?
No, currently registering non-Pega applications requires using custom connectors. After you register a non-Pega application, you can manage the application directly from Pega Process Fabric Hub interface, as any other Pega remote application.

For more information, see Managing applications in Pega Process Fabric Hub and Building custom connectors for Pega Process Fabric Hub.

Does Pega Process Fabric Hub check environment production level of an application to register?
Pega Process Fabric Hub checks the environment production level of an application that you want to register. To avoid unexpected issues with data, register applications from a system which production level is exactly same as the Pega Process Fabric Hub production level. For example, if Pega Process Fabric Hub is in staging environment, as a best practice register applications from the staging environment only. If you register an application which production level is different from Pega Process Fabric Hub, you receive a warning that states the environment mismatch. You can continue registering the application by accepting the data issues warning, and after the registration you can perform all application life cycle actions. If you use APIs, you an receive an error while registering an application that is of different production level.

Security
What security aspects are important to consider regarding Pega Process Fabric Hub?
Before you implement Pega Process Fabric Hub, consider the following security aspects:
Use single sign-on to configure the operators that you want to log in to Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Ensure that the operator ID of a user who wants to log in to Pega Process Fabric Hub is consistent across all registered applications and Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Configure security and access settings in the applications that you want to register with Pega Process Fabric Hub. Pega Process Fabric Hub fetches the configurations from the registered applications, and you cannot make any security modifications on the Pega Process Fabric Hub side.
For more information, see Operators and Authentication .

How does Pega Process Fabric Hub manage security? Does Pega Process Fabric Hub pull data from remote applications, or do remote applications publish data to Pega Process Fabric Hub?
The entire security configuration relies on the remote application that you register with Pega Process Fabric Hub. The remote application sends data, while Pega Process Fabric Hub only fetches assignment-related data. From the Pega Process Fabric Hub side, the risk of any data breach is nonexistent.

How does Pega Process Fabric Hub handle security aspects of remote applications, such as attribute-based access control (ABAC) or role-based access control (RBAC)?
Remote applications do not publish any data or configurations related to ABAC or RBAC to Pega Process Fabric Hub. A remote application considers security configurations when it opens an assignment in a new browser tab, after the redirect from Pega Process Fabric Hub.

For more information, see Role-based access control and Attribute-based access control .

What is the authentication mechanism between remote applications and Pega Process Fabric Hub?
Pega Process Fabric Hub uses REST APIs to connect to and accept data from remote applications. The REST endpoints rely on OAuth 2.0 authentication.

For more information, see Creating a secure connection with Pega Process Fabric Hub by configuring OAuth 2.0 authentication.

Communication with remote applications
How does Pega Process Fabric Hub communicate with registered applications to synchronize data?
For Pega Platform applications version 8.1 and later, Pega Process Fabric Hub synchronizes data through bidirectional API calls. Pega Process Fabric Hub can trigger an API call, but the synchronization occurs on the remote application side. Ensure that applications that you want to register with Pega Process Fabric Hub can process REST APIs correctly.

For a non-Pega remote application, you need to build a connection by using the Pega Process Fabric APIs. For non-Pega applications, Pega Process Fabric Hub does not trigger any API calls and the entire synchronization and communication process relies on the remote application.

For more information, see Accessing and testing Pega Traditional DX API .

What additional information about assignments does Pega Process Fabric Hub accept from remote applications?
Apart from standard assignment data, such as mapping to a worklist or a work queue, Pega Process Fabric Hub has three additional fields to store information: Customer, Product, and Account. To adjust mapping of fields between your remote Pega Platform application and Pega Process Fabric Hub, you can override the standard extension points that you obtain after installing Pega Process Fabric Hub.

For more information, see Modification of the standard mappings published to Pega Process Fabric Hub.

Can I modify which data fields that my remote application publishes to Pega Process Fabric Hub?
Yes, you can override the default values that a remote application passes to Pega Process Fabric Hub by using extensions that support a data model in Pega Process Fabric Hub. Pega Process Fabric Hub lacks support to customize its internal data model and accept customized values.

For more information, see Modification of the standard mappings published to Pega Process Fabric Hub.

Pega Process Fabric Hub and cloud environments
Can I use one instance of Pega Process Fabric Hub to manage both applications that I host in the Pega Cloud services environment and on the premises?
Yes, however, ensure that you configure Pega Process Fabric Hub to accept data from all types of environments where you host your applications.

For more information, see Setting up Pega Process Fabric Hub and Preparing Pega Process Fabric Hub for the Pega Cloud services environment.

Can I install Pega Process Fabric Hub in the Pega Cloud services environment?
You can install Pega Process Fabric Hub both on the premises and in a cloud environment, such as Pega Cloud or a client-managed cloud. If you install Pega Process Fabric Hub on the premises, you complete an entire installation process. When you use Pega Cloud, the Pega Cloud services team deploy Pega Process Fabric Hub for you. To request that Pega Cloud services install and configure Pega Process Fabric Hub in your environment, you must make a request by selecting New request in My Support Portal, and include the networking details and operator details in the request. For the latest documentation on making requests, see My Support Portal: New Design, Streamlined Features. Ensure that you request hosting Pega Process Fabric Hub on an HTTPS port.

What do I do after the Pega Cloud services deploy Pega Process Fabric Hub for me?
After the deployment, your instance of Pega Process Fabric Hub includes all necessary rulesets. Pega Cloud services do not perform any additional configuration, such as assigning access groups to users. Continue with creating an administrative user and enabling a default operator that Pega Process Fabric Hub adds to your application, and that is disabled for applications on Pega Cloud. For more information, see Creating an administrative user for Pega Process Fabric Hub and Preparing Pega Process Fabric Hub for the Pega Cloud services environment.

For more information, see Creating an administrative user for Pega Process Fabric Hub.

Do I need to create separate service requests for different staging environments?
Yes, if you host your instance of Pega Process Fabric Hub on Pega Cloud, you need to create a service request when you want to deploy Pega Process Fabric Hub on different staging environments, such as testing or production.

How does Pega Process Fabric Hub on cloud communicate with remote applications if I use multiple instances to host applications?
The communication model depends on instances that you use and is different for public and private access. For example, if you host Pega Process Fabric Hub in a cloud environment and your remote applications on the premises, and you use public access through the Internet, you only configure OAuth 2.0 authentication. For more information about different deployment scenarios, see Communication models of remote applications and Pega Process Fabric Hub.

If I deploy Pega Process Fabric Hub in a cloud environment, do I need to configure any network configurations?
To ensure communication between your remote applications and Pega Process Fabric Hub, create a service request in My Support Portal requiring the following actions:
Listing Pega Process Fabric Hub in the allow list of your remote application.
Listing the remote application in the allow list of Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Additional questions
How does upgrading applications that have the Pega Process Fabric Hub connector affect communication of these applications with Pega Process Fabric Hub?
You can add the Pega Process Fabric Hub connector to an application that you host in Pega Platform version 8.1 or later. If you update your instance of Pega Platform to a version higher than 8.1, the connections between remote applications that this instance of Pega Platform hosts and Pega Process Fabric Hub continue to work without the need for any additional configurations. As a best practice, to avoid any issues with data synchronization, update the connector to match the current version of the Pega Platform instance that hosts your remote application. For more information, see Installing the Pega Process Fabric Hub connector component.

Does Pega Process Fabric Hub display assignments from remote applications as mashup code?
No, Pega Process Fabric Hub opens assignments from remote applications in new browser tabs.

Does Pega Process Fabric Hub support Federated Case Management?
No, Pega Process Fabric Hub does not support Federated Case Management or Federated Case Management Repository. Federated Case Management Repository is deprecated and is incompatible with applications that you host in Pega Platform version 8.1 and later.

Does Pega Process Fabric Hub support collaboration tools, such as Pulse or spaces?
Currently, Pega Process Fabric Hub does not support collaboration tools. You can install and use collaboration tools directly in your remote applications.

For more information, see Collaborating on cases .

Can I use built-on applications to extend the features of Pega Process Fabric Hub?
Although Pega Process Fabric Hub is an application that you can extend as any other Pega Platform application, avoid customizations and overrides to prevent any issues that might occur when you update to a newer version of Pega Process Fabric Hub.

Can I customize the UI of Pega Process Fabric Hub to meet my unique needs?
No, currently, Pega Process Fabric Hub does not support any UI customizations.

Pega Process Fabric Hub opens assignments in new browser tabs. How do remote applications handle session management?
An application reuses the same browser session. If a user opens one assignment multiple times in multiple tabs, all the redirects from Pega Process Fabric Hub use the same thread name, which then refreshes all other sessions. As a best practice, close a tab after completing an assignment.

How does Pega Process Fabric Hub use websockets?
Pega Process Fabric Hub uses websockets on a server. When a change in a remote application occurs, the remote application publishes data to Pega Process Fabric Hub through REST APIs. The server on the Pega Process Fabric Hub side publishes the changes to the websockets and refreshes the UI in Pega Process Fabric Hub. You do not need to perform any additional browser session configurations.

Configure remote case creation for case workers that use multiple Pega Platform applications. By using this functionality, you can create cases for different applications directly from Pega Process Fabric Hub, which speeds up work processing.

You configure the remote cases creation option in Pega Process Fabric Hub by performing the following tasks:https://docs.pega.com/bundle/pega-process-fabric-hub-21/page/platform/pega-process-fabric/Obtaining-case-creation-URL-remote-application.html

Obtaining a case creation URL in your remote application
Generate a case creation URL in your remote application to help you configure the creation of remote cases from the Pega Process Fabric Hub portal. By configuring remote case creation, you can start creating cases from different applications directly in Pega Process Fabric Hub.

A case creation URL is a combination of a system URL and an encrypted case type URL. You obtain the URLs in your remote application.

Before you begin:
Ensure that you obtain the case creation URL for each of your registered remote applications and for each case type from which you want to create remote cases in Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Open your remote Pega Platform application.
In the URL bar, select and copy the system URL in the following format: https://domain/context-root/auth-servlet-path.
In the navigation pane of Dev Studio, click Records.
Expand the Technical category, and then click Activity.
In the list of activities, select and open the pzTestActivity activity that applies to the -Work class, and then click Save As.
Click Create and open.
On the Steps tab, in the first step, in the Method field, enter Property-Set.
Click the Expand to see method parameters icon.
In the PropertiesName field, enter a name for the property, for example Param.URL.
Next to the PropertiesValue field, click Build an expression.
In the Expression builder dialog box, combine the system URL and a function name to obtain the encrypted case type URL by entering an expression in the following format:
"The system URL"+@(Pega-RULES:Utilities).pzEncryptURLActionString(tools,"Global","pyActivity=pyMobileSnapStart&Action=createWork&InsClass=your case type class name&FlowType=pyStartCase&HarnessPurpose=New&pyShowFullPortal=true&ThreadName=CreateWork")
The pzEncryptURLActionString function requires parameters in the following format:pega_rules_utilities.pzEncryptURLActionString(PublicAPI,Scope,caseURL).

For example:
"https://domain/context-root/auth-servlet-path?"+@(Pega-RULES:Utilities).pzEncryptURLActionString(tools,"Global","pyActivity=pyMobileSnapStart&Action=createWork&InsClass=OZJ1B8-Interaction-Work-Timesheet&FlowType=pyStartCase&HarnessPurpose=New&pyShowFullPortal=true&ThreadName=CreateWork")
Click Submit.
Click Add item, and then, in the Method field, enter Show-Property.
Click Expand to see method parameters, and then, in the Value field, enter Param.URL.
On the activity form, click Save.
In the Actions menu, click Run, and then copy and save the result for later use in your Pega Process Fabric Hub.
For example:
https://domain/context-root/auth-servlet-path? pzuiactionzzz=CXtpbn1lYXVjT0FhYjd5MjlYdzczN1M4Q3FKaWZrT1ByaVFzOFFOYUtHL0p0SWNLUHdBNElnMTZyU1lRQnNXb0dJTzdsc1RPUDR6b21iYTRNWmNqckwvT1VYQzhjdk9VK2xTRWNUUEx3WnhxQ1J1blRDUWVtaUxmQm5yeFNNU0V0d0xUSWZjOVpQakJObUppbXV0c2I1eTB0RmxOTzBSYW91OXBHSzhQcEJMd3hHRThCTWtVcm85VEF6M0RabmxQdmU5Vkw%3D*
.
Optional: To obtain the case creation URL for more case types, click Add item, and then repeat steps 7 through 16 for each case type that you want to use in any of your registered applications.

Extending Pega Process Fabric Hub data model with additional fields
With additional fields, you can present more detailed data in your Pega Process Fabric Hub to meet your unique business scenario needs.For example, you can add an assignment field that corresponds with a geographic region that is related to the assignment. Consequently, you can conveniently filter your worklist and reports by the regions in which your company operates. For operator mappings, you can add fields that represent a specific skill and skill rating for an operator. As a result, you improve routing of assignments and the Next Best Work algorithm in Pega Process Fabric Hub.
To pass additional data to Pega Process Fabric Hub, you can extend your data model by adding the following types of fields:
assignment fields
operator mapping fields
case fields
case to operator association fields

Exploring assignment data with Pega Process Fabric Hub Insights
Pega Process Fabric Hub Insights is a tool that you can use to get a holistic view of a workflow in your organization by analyzing real-time data about assignments that remote applications publish to Pega Process Fabric Hub. As a result, you can ensure that users resolve tasks within defined timelines, identify and fix bottlenecks, and ultimately improve workload management.

Pega Process Fabric Hub Insights displays consolidated information about assignments from registered applications, such as a number of new and resolved assignments within a specified time frame, for example, from the last seven days. You can also conveniently check how many assignments are currently open and overdue. By analyzing the consolidated data about all the assignments from your applications that are registered in Pega Process Fabric Hub, you can make informed decisions about workload in your organization, without switching between multiple applications. Pega Process Fabric Hub Insights helps you dynamically respond to any issues that might occur, such as high-priority assignments with a past deadline.

For example:
Consider a scenario in which a number of tasks across different applications that are routed to one user are high priority and overdue. By using Pega Process Fabric Hub Insights, you can quickly identify the issue, check which user is overloaded, and which application routed the assignments. To ensure that the workflow is continuous and uninterrupted, you can implement relevant solutions. For example, you can log in to an application that routes the assignments, and then reassign the tasks to other users with higher availability. To access Pega Process Fabric Hub Insights, ensure that you have the PPF:Managers access group

Building custom connectors for Pega Process Fabric Hub
Pega Process Fabric Hub is an application that consolidates assignments from multiple distributed applications, in order to speed up work processing and provide a comprehensive overview of the workflows in your organization. To incorporate non-Pega applications into centralized work processing, you can implement custom connectors to create communication with Pega Process Fabric Hub.

Pega Process Fabric Hub uses open APIs to collect assignment data from distributed applications. Pega Process Fabric Hub then implements the collected information across unified worklists and work queues, the Next Best Work algorithm, and reports that users with managerial roles can view in Pega Process Fabric Hub Insights. When you create a connection between Pega Process Fabric Hub and an application that you build in Pega Platform version 8.1 or later, you use the default Pega Process Fabric Hub connector. For your non-Pega applications, implement the Pega Process Fabric Hub APIs and publish the data.

You can connect your non-Pega application to Pega Process Fabric Hub provided that the remote application supports invoking the Pega Process Fabric Hub APIs to publish the assignment data. Pega Process Fabric Hub utilizes the following APIs:
Registration APIs
Use the registration APIs to create a connection between your remote application and Pega Process Fabric Hub, and then manage the application life cycle, for example, to resynchronize the application or delete the connection between your application and Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Data synchronization APIs
Use the data synchronization APIs to sync assignment data from your remote applications with Pega Process Fabric Hub.
The following figure describes the communication between Pega Process Fabric Hub and remote applications. Applications that you deploy in Pega Platform use the Pega Process Fabric Hub connector, while third-party applications use the Pega Process Fabric Hub APIs:
A diagram that presents how Pega Process Fabric Hub communicates with Pega and non-Pega applications
Communication between Pega Process Fabric Hub and remote applications
Note: As a best practice, use custom connectors only for non-Pega applications. For applications that you build in Pega Platform, download the Pega Process Fabric Hub connector component from Pega Marketplace. For more information, see Process Fabric Connector for Pega Platform.
Requirements for applications that you connect to Pega Process Fabric Hub
Before you connect your third-party application to Pega Process Fabric Hub, ensure that your application meets the following requirements:
Pega Process Fabric Hub accepts assignment metadata that the registered remote applications publish by using REST APIs. Ensure that the remote application can pass assignment metadata by invoking the Pega Process Fabric Hub APIs, either through itself or through an intermediate logic, which is a connector.
Ensure that the operator ID for specific users is identical across all registered applications, including Pega Process Fabric Hub.
Ensure that your remote application publishes the data of assignments that can be processed by users in your organization who have access to the application. Avoid publishing the data of assignments that users cannot process for any reason.
